4":"1080–1114","1080–Female":"1080–Overleden","1080":"1080","1103":"1103","1114":"1114","1112":"1112","1133":"1133","1110":"1110","liv 1124":"1124","1173":"1173","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1103–":"1103–Deceased","1103–Male":"1103–Deceased","1112–Male":"1112–Deceased","1110–Female":"1110–Deceased","1133–1173":"1133–1173","–Male":"Deceased","1080–1114":"1080–1114","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1080":"1080","1103":"1103","1114":"1114","1112":"1112","1133":"1133","1110":"1110","liv 1124":"1124","1173":"1173","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Kilpek was born in 1103, his father, William de la Mare of Kilpek, was 23 and his mother, Maud d'Avranches, was 24. He married Meirig ap Griffin. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1103–":"1103–Surnud","1103–Male":"1103–Surnud","1112–Male":"1112–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1133–1173":"1133–1173","–Male":"Surnud","1080–1114":"1080–1114","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1103":"1103","1114":"1114","1112":"1112","1133":"1133","1110":"1110","liv 1124":"1124","1173":"1173","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1103–":"1103–Kuollut","1103–Male":"1103–Kuollut","1112–Male":"1112–Kuollut","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1133–1173":"1133–1173","–Male":"Kuollut","1080–1114":"1080–1114","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1103":"1103","1114":"1114","1112":"1112","1133":"1133","1110":"1110","liv 1124":"1124","1173":"1173","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"1103–":"1103–Décédé","1103–Male":"1103–Décédé","1112–Male":"1112–Décédé","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","1133–1173":"1133–1173","–Male":"Décédé","1080–1114":"1080–1114","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1080":"1080","1103":"1103","1114":"1114","1112":"1112","1133":"1133","1110"